2026-04-21 01:40:50 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module timing / sensor network associated with the ambient light sensor and comparator (e.g., RC timing components or bias network causing oscillation)'] hypothesis_explanation='All supply-path elements are stable: the battery, PSU output, control‑module I/O rails, relay contacts, load‑module input, series diode, and both lamps all show steady voltages with no drop during the observed operation. The relay coil has essentially zero differential voltage (both ends at ~11.85 V), so it is continuously energized and not responsible for the periodic 0.5 s lamp turn‑off.\n\nThe only subsystem not yet directly verified dynamically is the internal timing/sensor network around the ambient‑light sensor and comparator. The system reports that this part of the control circuit is in an unstable or oscillating state. A slow (~20 s) oscillation arising from an incorrectly biased comparator, faulty RC timing component, or mis‑configured sensitivity/timing network can periodically drive the comparator output into a state that momentarily disables or perturbs the lamp drive, producing the observed 0.5 s dropouts even though the relay and supply voltages appear static under spot measurements.\n\nBecause the rest of the power path is confirmed good and the oscillation is localized by the simulation to the control module’s timing/sensor section, the root cause is most likely a fault in the timing/sensor network components (e.g., a leaky capacitor, wrong‑value resistor, or other defect causing an unintended relaxation oscillator behavior). Repairing/replacing the faulty elements in this timing/sensor network should eliminate the 20 s periodic lamp interruptions.'
