2026-04-21 01:41:08 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module relay contacts (welded or permanently closed)', 'control module internal wiring that should place the relay in series with the 12 V path to the load'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage measurements show a solid, uninterrupted 12 V path from the battery to the load module, including through the control module, during operation and across multiple 20‑second cycles. The relay coil has essentially 0 V across it (both terminals at ~11.85 V to ground), and the control‑module input and output cables, as well as the relay switched contacts, all sit at the same ~11.85 V. This means the relay is never actually modulating the 12 V supply to the lamp. Yet the lamp still exhibits a brief 0.5 s turn‑off every ~20 s.\n\nSince the earlier hypothesis that the timing/sensor network is oscillating was disproven by replacement, and the power‑supply and load modules have been verified stable, the remaining plausible fault consistent with: (a) constant 12 V through the supposed ‘switched’ path, (b) no detectable relay‑coil drive, and (c) persistent periodic lamp dropout, is that the relay contacts (or the wiring that should route the 12 V through them) are misconfigured or welded closed such that the control module no longer really controls the lamp. The observed 20‑second off interval must therefore originate elsewhere (e.g., external to this circuit or due to intermittent contact at a different point), but the only internal defect that matches all electrical observations is a failed control element that is permanently conducting.\n\nThus I hypothesize that the relay contact set or its series wiring is faulty—effectively shorted closed—so the control module cannot interrupt the load even when commanded. Repairing/replacing the relay contact assembly and restoring the correct series routing of the 12 V through it should correct the abnormal behavior and restore proper control, eliminating the unexplained periodic dropouts once the system is rewired as designed.'
