2026-04-21 01:41:17 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module – main lamp filament or internal lamp connection exhibiting intermittent open/high resistance when hot'] hypothesis_explanation='All upstream measurements (battery, PSU output, control‑module input and output, relay contacts, load‑input terminals, and diode) remain steady at about 11.8–12.0 V with no drop or interruption over the observed period, and both relay coil terminals sit at the supply positive, indicating the control module is not switching the load. Thus the 0.5 s every‑20‑s dark interval of the external lamp occurs while the supply to the load module remains constant. This rules out faults in the battery, PSU wiring, control‑module timing/sensor network, relay drive, and relay contacts (all previously tested or even replaced with no effect). The only remaining plausible cause consistent with: (1) constant 11.0–11.1 V present at the lamp node, (2) no polarity problems, (3) the internal indicator lamp not reported as flickering, and (4) the symptom describing only the visible lamp turning off, is an intermittent open or high‑resistance condition local to the main lamp itself (or its immediate internal connection) that occurs thermally/periodically. When the main lamp opens, its branch current collapses, making the external lamp appear off despite the node voltage staying near nominal; the parallel small indicator lamp is less noticeable to the observer, so its continued operation was not perceived as a fault. Replacing or repairing the main lamp element or its internal wiring in the load module should eliminate the periodic brief turn‑off observed at the main lamp.'
