2026-04-21 01:41:45 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module – polarity / I/O cable connections between power‑supply, control, and load modules (specifically, miswired or cross‑connected positive and negative leads)'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements show a stable 12 V supply, steady relay state, and constant voltage across the load, and a direct observation confirms that, electrically, the lamps and PSU LED never actually turn off or dim during the purported 0.5 s dropouts. The earlier hypotheses about internal component faults (sensor network, relay contacts, lamp filament, or measurement artifact) have been experimentally eliminated by repair attempts that produced no change in behavior. The only remaining plausible cause consistent with: (1) stable voltages and currents in all modules, (2) relay coil and contacts both seeing full supply with virtually zero voltage across the coil, and (3) the system simulation repeatedly reporting a non‑convergent or oscillating state while the physical indicators remain steady, is an incorrect external wiring/polarity configuration of the control module cables.\n\nBecause the modules are designed so that the cables can be swapped or polarity‑reversed at each interface, connecting the positive and negative leads incorrectly (e.g., crossing the 2‑wire pairs between the PSU and control module or between the control module and load, or reversing one pair) can leave the internal electronics operating normally relative to their own local ground while making the overall series path behave abnormally from the perspective of the rest of the system and the simulator. This misconnection can create apparent oscillation or non‑convergence in the modeled circuit without causing obvious voltage drops at the measured points, and can easily explain the mismatch between the initially reported symptom (periodic lamp outage) and the later direct observation (no actual dropout).\n\nTherefore, the most likely root cause is that the external I/O cables of the control module are miswired or polarity‑reversed relative to the power supply and load modules. Correcting the wiring so that each module’s + and − terminals are connected in the intended orientation and each 2‑wire pair goes to the proper mate should restore proper, stable operation and eliminate the apparent fault.'
