2026-04-21 01:42:11 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module – internal “switched‑cables indicator” LED (and its series resistor / branch from the switched 12 V path)'] hypothesis_explanation='All three functional modules (battery/PSU, relay path, and load including both lamps and series diode) have now been effectively cleared: measured voltages remain stable at all points (battery, PSU output, control I/O, load input, diode, lamp node, and across both lamps) and direct observation shows no actual dropout of any of the three visible lights. The relay coil has essentially zero differential voltage and its contacts show the same potential on both sides, confirming the relay is simply held closed and is not cycling. The timing/sensor network has been replaced without effect, and cable polarity and wiring between modules have been verified. \n\nYet the simulation continues to report that the circuit is in an “unstable or oscillating state” at ~20 s, and the original symptom description refers to a perceived lamp dropout every ~20 s. Since no actual interruption occurs in the power or load path, the only remaining element that can create an internal, low‑level oscillation without affecting lamp voltage is the small indicator LED branch inside the control module labeled as the switched‑cables indicator. If this LED (or its series resistor or local wiring) were faulty—e.g., intermittently shorting, partially shorted, or otherwise interacting with the sensor/comparator node—it could produce a small internal oscillation or current perturbation that the simulator flags as instability while never pulling the 12 V rail or the relay sufficiently to change lamp state. \n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a fault in the control module’s internal switched‑cables indicator LED circuit, not in the main relay path or the external wiring. Repairing or replacing this indicator branch should remove the residual oscillatory behaviour reported by the system without altering the already‑stable lamp operation.'
