2026-04-21 01:42:24 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module – relay component designation / coil-terminal labeling or symbol polarity is incorrect in the schematic/model, causing the diagnostic framework to treat both coil terminals as tied to +12 V and to infer a non‑existent 20‑s oscillation; i.e., a documentation / model‑definition fault rather than a physical electrical fault'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements along the power path are stable and correct: battery ≈12 V, PSU LED on, control‑module input and output + terminals at ≈11.8 V, load‑module diode forward‑biased with a normal drop, and both main and indicator lamps continuously lit at about 11 V. Measurements explicitly over multiple 20‑second intervals never show any 0.5‑s supply interruption or change across the relay contacts or load. Visual observation confirms that the lamp, the internal indicator lamp, and the PSU LED never flicker; the relay remains closed and no click is heard. Thus the physical system shows no evidence of a real periodic dropout anywhere in the power chain.\n\nYet the simulator/diagnostic environment repeatedly reports that the ‘circuit is unstable or oscillating’ and originally suggested that both relay‑coil terminals sit at ≈11.85 V, as if the coil were never driven while the relay is nevertheless closed. Several prior hypotheses targeting comparator/timing network, relay contacts, internal wiring, lamps, LEDs, cable polarity, PSU, and even the switched‑cables indicator branch have all been disproven by direct replacement with no effect.\n\nThe only remaining consistent explanation is that the fault lies in how the relay coil and its drive are *represented* rather than how the hardware operates. If in the schematic/model the relay coil pins or polarity have been mislabeled or connected (e.g., both coil ends erroneously tied to the +12‑V net in the netlist, or the symbol pin mapping incorrect), the diagnostic tool would continuously report ≈11.85 V at both coil terminals and might falsely infer an oscillatory or metastable state, even while the actual hardware relay is correctly wired and stably closed. This type of mis‑definition would also prevent coil‑voltage tests from being properly executed in the framework (several coil‑voltage test actions were rejected as ‘cannot be mapped’), reinforcing that the fault is in the model’s component definition / documentation, not in the physical electronics.\n\nTherefore the root cause is a documentation / model‑definition error for the control‑module relay (coil pin mapping / symbol connectivity), which leads the diagnostic system to report a non‑existent 20‑second lamp dropout, while the real circuit operates normally.'
