2026-04-21 01:42:34 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module – ambient light sensor input connection (open / not connected to sensor)', 'control module – comparator non‑inverting input node (floating due to broken trace or solder joint)'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage and continuity tests show a healthy 12 V supply, correct polarity through all modules, proper operation of the load‑module diode and lamps, and a relay that remains effectively constantly energized (both coil and contact nodes sitting at ~11.8 V with no measured drops). Adjusting the timing potentiometer and changing ambient illumination have no influence on behaviour, and the observed 0.5 s lamp dropout cannot be reproduced when the system is closely observed (main lamp, internal lamp, and PSU LED all remain continuously lit). \n\nThe only abnormal electrical reading is at the ambient‑light sensor side of the control module: its positive node sits near mid‑supply (~5.94 V) while the negative side is near 0 V, yet the relay drive and switched path stay fixed high. This is consistent with the comparator input node being left floating or biased internally to some default level because the light sensor is effectively disconnected (open circuit) from the comparator input. In that case, varying ambient light or the timing/sensitivity controls would not appreciably change the comparator output, so the relay remains in one state regardless of environment, and the sensor loop can exhibit apparent “unstable/oscillating” reports in simulation even though the physical outputs don’t move.\n\nTherefore the most plausible root cause, consistent with all unsuccessful previous repairs, is a connectivity fault in the control module around the ambient‑light sensor input—specifically an open connection (broken PCB trace, cracked solder joint, or unconnected lead) between the light sensor element and the comparator’s non‑inverting input node, leaving that comparator input floating and insensitive to actual ambient light.'
