2026-04-21 01:42:47 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module – ambient light sensor element itself is mis‑installed or mis‑oriented (e.g., photodiode / LDR wired with reversed polarity or wrong terminals), causing the control circuit to operate in an unintended regime that produces the apparent 20‑second unstable/oscillating state while still keeping the relay permanently closed and the lamps continuously on'] hypothesis_explanation='All measured nodes in the power‑supply, relay path, and load module are stable: the PSU LED is steadily on, the relay contacts and output cables sit continuously at ~11.8 V, and the load‑module diode and lamps see a constant ~11 V with both lamps lit and never dropping out when directly observed. That excludes an intermittent in the supply, relay contacts/coil drive, wiring polarity, and both lamps; previous repair attempts have also ruled those out individually.\n\nYet the diagnostic framework repeatedly reports the control circuit as being in an “unstable or oscillating state,” and the original user symptom is that the lamp appears to turn off briefly every ~20 s. Since no real 20‑s voltage or current modulation can be found anywhere along the actual power path, the only remaining plausible root cause is that the sensor side of the control module is behaving abnormally, driving the internal comparator into a regime that the simulation/diagnostics interpret as instability, while the relay remains effectively forced closed.\n\nWe already ruled out broken or floating sensor/comparator connections and timing‑network component faults by replacement. A consistent way to obtain such a behavior is a mis‑installed or mis‑oriented light sensor device: for example, a photodiode or photo‑transistor mounted backwards, or an LDR wired to the opposite comparator input or to the wrong pads. The measured sensor node voltages (~5.94 V vs ~0.023 V) show a fully biased divider, not an open circuit, but if the sensor polarity/terminal mapping is wrong, the comparator may saturate in the ‘relay ON’ direction regardless of actual light, while its internal model indicates an oscillatory operating point.\n\nThus, the root cause is most likely a build‑time assembly error specific to the ambient light sensor element inside the control module (wrong orientation/terminal wiring), not a failure of otherwise correctly wired components. Repair would consist in reinstalling the sensor with the correct orientation/terminal connections according to the intended schematic.'
