2026-04-21 01:43:42 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module – internal comparator / relay‑drive output node stuck permanently high (saturated), preventing any actual 20‑s switching of the relay or load despite the originally reported symptom'] hypothesis_explanation='All direct electrical measurements show a healthy, static DC system:\n- PSU LED is steadily on and the 12 V output is stable.\n- Both control‑module I/O positives sit at ~11.8 V, negatives at ~0 V, with solid ground continuity.\n- The relay contacts show ~11.8 V on both sides; the output to the load is a constant ~11.8 V.\n- The relay coil terminals each sit at ~11.8 V to ground, implying essentially 0 V across the coil, so it is never being driven.\n- The ambient‑sensor node is biased at about 6 V vs ~0 V on its other side, consistent with a valid sensor bias, and this also appears static.\n- The load‑module diode and both lamps see a steady ~11 V and are observed to be continuously lit; repeated observations in a dark environment show no real 20‑s dropout.\n\nTherefore there is no evidence of any real 20‑s variation anywhere in the power path or control path. The only consistent explanation for the combination of: (a) a reported 20‑s oscillation state in the control module, but (b) relay coil with ~0 V across it and contacts permanently passing 12 V, is that the comparator/driver stage that should switch the relay is internally stuck in its high (relay‑on) state. Electrically this presents as a saturated high output feeding both sides of the relay coil through the same potential, so no current flows and the relay never actually toggles, regardless of the intended 20‑s timing. The rest of the circuit operates correctly with a constant closed path to the lamp.\n\nOther modules (battery, lamps, diode, sensor, wiring, ground) have effectively been cleared by measurement and previous unsuccessful repair attempts. The fault is most plausibly localized to the comparator / relay‑drive output node within the control module being latched or shorted to the positive rail, i.e. the comparator or its immediate drive transistor is defective even though the rest of the timing network is intact.'
